<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-515-890  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 515 890.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 4 1990 v24 n23 pSR5(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Graphical user interfaces: beyond fun and games. (businesssoftware taking cues from computer game industry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hurwitz, Judith S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Graphical user interface designs in the 1990s will borrow from thedesign of children's educational and entertainment software, whichrequire intuitive operation and an easy-to-understand metaphor.andO;Future user interfaces will empower individuals to improve thecompetitiveness of their businesses and for 'ad hoc' work groupsto develop targeted short-term projects for customer benefit.andO;User interfaces need to be consistent at the developer tool kitand application programming interface levels so that developersneed only write one set of protocols.andP;  Development will then shiftto the end-user layers, and interfaces designed on the basis ofparticular jobs will appear.andP;  Multimedia technologies will letbusiness software offer the sound and motion capabilities nowfound in computer games.andP;  Interfaces in the 1990s will also allowaccess to real-time data, and touch screens will become common.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceForecastingFuture of Computing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>